All Being is either a subject of attributeS, or one of the attri- butes themselves. In the former case, it is Substance, In the latter, the attribute’s existence is either in itself or in other beings. If in itself, and at the same time it gives its subjects intensive parts or degreeS, either of entity or of imperfection, it is called Quality. If the subject receives from it only extensive parts, which differ from quality by being mutually exclusive, each one outside of the other (partes extra partes) we have Quantiyf. If the attribute only exists in (or for) other beings (ad aliud, πρός τι.) it either indicates 3 change or a fixed state. If a change, we have the two corresponding.
